Of the first Parliament of James 111„ held at Edinburgh 231d February 1460-1,1 of which the record has not been preserved, there is a brief notice in the Asloan Ms. To that Parliament, says the Chronicler, “ come thir lordis under writtin, that is to say the Lord of Ylis and Erll of Ros, and all the lardis os the Ilis, Lord Dernlie, and the Lord Kalenclar, the Lord Hammiltoun. And thai (lid litill gud in the sorsaicl Parliament, but that thai ordanit sessionis to sit, first at Aberdene, syne in Perth, syne in Eclinburgh. And thai left the king in keping with his moder the quene, and governyng of all the kinrik. And therfor the lorclis said that thai war littil gud worth, bath spirituale ancl tempora-ll, that gaf the keping of the kinrik till a woman.''2
